600 1805 1436 (As identified by Beman Dawes in lib-3367, the 20 September 1994 draft of the) 1436 SB
600 1856 1464 (WP does not include getline\(\) .  It was part of the 27 May 1994 draft of the WP.) 1464 SB
600 1907 1458 (Beman suggested that getline\(\) be reinstated with the semantics as specified in) 1458 SB
600 1958 380 (the earlier WP draft.) 380 SB
600 2060 903 (In lib-3408, Nathan Myers responded as follows:) 903 SB
600 2111 21 (\223) 21 SB
gs 1773 3231 621 0 CB
621 2111 1437 (I\222m quite concerned about the semantics implied in the string traits.  There, it) 1437 SB
gr
600 2162 1479 (seems to be assumed that the end-of-line character is the same for all encodings) 1479 SB
600 2213 1467 (of a character type.  But, of course, even in ASCII we see an amazing variety of) 1467 SB
600 2264 1443 (line-end conventions.  Unicode is worse, with all the ASCII control characters) 1443 SB
600 2315 852 (and \(as I recall\) two more line-end characters.) 852 SB
600 2417 21 (\223) 21 SB
gs 1773 3231 621 0 CB
621 2417 1471 (I fear that we cannot provide internationalized getline semantics with the same) 1471 SB
gr
600 2468 1393 (interface that we have had.  I can imagine a getline\(\) which takes the user\222s) 1393 SB
600 2519 1380 (choice of line ending, but I can imagine you may want any of the available) 1380 SB
600 2570 1341 (choices to end a line.  The locale object\222s ctype facet does not provide an) 1341 SB
600 2621 1321 (\221is_eol\(\)\222 member, and POSIX does not provide the underlying support) 1321 SB
600 2672 703 (necessary to implement it in any case.) 703 SB
600 2774 21 (\223) 21 SB
gs 1773 3231 621 0 CB
621 2774 1341 (It seems clear to me that the getline operation depends on the character-) 1341 SB
gr
600 2825 1463 (encoding in use, and that makes it a locale-dependent operation.  It is not clear) 1463 SB
600 2876 1385 (to me how to propagate the information to the place where it is needed.  It) 1385 SB
